en: The History of the most Ingenious Knight Don Quixote de la Mancha
Don Quixote Dubb'd a Knight Errant by the Innkeeper
3.3 Fight with muleteer3.4 DQ knighted at inn by innkeeper

This illustration is a copy of that by Bouttats (Amberes: Verdussen, 1672 - 1673). The episode did not appear among the 24 illustrated by Savery (Dordrecht: Savery, 1657). Two different scenes. The first one is in the background: don Quixote fights with the muleteers during the vigil of his arms; the second one is in the foreground: don Quixote is knighted by the innkeeper while doña Molinera fits his spurs and doña Tolosa his sword. The boy whith a candle that appears in Cervantes' text is missing.Illustration done with few details and with very basic burin lines.

Cushing's copy appears newly guillotined and titles are partial or totally cut. We have taken them from another complete copy.In our copy the frontispieces for Part I and Part II are missing. They were both the same: a copy engraved and signed by Michael van der Gucht of that by Savery for Part I (Dordrecht: Savery, 1657). Michael van der Gucht included under the right pedestal Merlin's medallion, that appears in Savery's Part II frontispiece.Michael van der Gucht (Amberes, 1660 - London, 1725): Flemish school engraver disciple of Frederik Bouttats in Amberes. He married Maria van Haghenberg in Amsterdam in 1682 and traveled to London to work for David Loggan. He was wellknown due to his anatomical figures and his illustration for the "England History" by Carendon. It is highlighted his "Savage portrait" (Benezit: 1976, V, 261).Frederik Bouttats "the Young" (? - 1676): Engraver in Amberes, he is one of the most important of 17th century. He engraved portraits of artists and personalities of his own time )Louis XIII, Felipe II King of Spain, Cristina Queen of Sweden, Cromwell, the Duke of Brabant, the architect L. van Heil, the painters J.-B. van Heil and David Ryckaert...), religious subjects and illustrations for several editions ("Images of men of spirit", 1649). In 1643, he was part of the Guild of Saint Luke in Amberes. He had twenty-four sons and daughters; some of them were engravers for publishers in Amberes and Colonia (Benezit: 1976, II, 249).
Don Quixote delivers a youth from Whipping
4.3 DQ frees Andrés from Juan Haldudo

This illustration copies that by Bouttats (Amberes: Verdussen, 1672 - 1673), who had re-organized Savery's composition (Dordrecht: Savery, 1657) changing the position of the characters in the foreground (Andrés and Juan Haldudo) and putting Rocinante at a gallop.The engraving is more detailed regarding the landscape.Don Quixote and Rocinante are drawn disproportionately.
The Buryal of the Shepherd Chrifoftome
14.2 Grisóstomo´s song14.3 Marcela’s appearance and speech14.4 Burial of Grisóstomo

Copy from Savery's composition (Dordrecht: Savery, 1657; Brussels: Mommarte, 1662; Amberes: Verdussen, 1672 - 1673). In the foreground, several shepherds are preparing Grisóstomo's grave. The background is divided in two parts: below, the dead shepherd, his friend Ambrosio, Vivaldo reading Grisóstomo's song and don Quixote; above, Marcela's appearance and speech. Marcela's figure copies Saint Gabriel's traditional image.The engraving is crude and the landscape not much detailed.

Previous to this illustration, there should be another two: "The Unfortunate Adventure of the Merchants. Don Quixote carry'd home upon an afs" (f.p. 21) and "Don Quixote Encounters the Windmills and ffights y Bifcainer" (f.p. 37).Jacob Savery or Savry or Savary III (Amsterdam, 1617 - Amsterdam, 1666?): Burin engraver and publisher. His father, Salomon Savery, was burin engraver too, painter and aquafortist. He worked in Amsterdam and Delft (Benezit: 1976, IX, 319).
Don Quixote & the Carrier fighting for the Innkeeper Maid

Copy from illustration by Savery (Dordrecht: Savery, 1657; Brussels: Mommarte, 1662; Amberes: Verdussen, 1672 - 1673). In the foreground, don Quixote lying over the broken bed; in the background, the fighting between Sancho, Maritornes and the muleteer is discovered by the innkeeper, who holds a candle.The engraving is crude (Maritornes is deformed, the engraver has not paid attention to the candle light effects, non-detailed inn...).
Sancho Tofs't in a blanket and Don Quixote's Encounter with a fflock of sheep

Copy from Savery's composition (Dordrecht: Savery, 1657; Brussels: Mommarte, 1662; Amberes: Verdussen, 1672 - 1673). Two different scenes in the same plate. In the foreground, Sancho's blanketing is observed by don Quixote from behind the inn wall. In the background, don Quixote fights a flock of sheep.The engraver is not good at representing movement and background figures are disproportioned.

Copy from Bouttats' composition (Amberes: Verdussen, 1672 - 1673), who engraved this episode for the first time. In the foreground, don Quixote defeats Alonso López; in the background, the funeral procession companions escape in great confussion.Figures are bigger in this illustration than in others; some of them (don Quixote and Rocinante) are disproportionated. The engraving, not much detailed, is acceptable, creating a good impression of movement.Torchs light effects are simple.
In Cushing's copy the title appears totally cut.
Don Quixote Releases the Galley slaves

Composition based on that by Bouttats (Amberes: Verdussen, 1672 - 1673). Two different scenes in the same illustration. In the foreground, don Quixote defeats one of the slave's guards, while Sancho releases the slaves. In the background, the consequence: don Quixote and Sancho Panza are stoned by the slaves.Shading burin lines are interesting in some parts (rocks).
In don Quixote's shield there appears a feminine figure that covers her mouth with her hands.
Cardenio the madman beats the Kight & Squire
24.1 Story of Cardenio24.3 Cardenio attacks DQ and SP

In the foreground, Cardenio fighting against don Quixote, fallen defeated, and Sancho, protecting his head; the goatherd arrives to help them.Simple composition.Drawing and engraving are bad and poor in details (Rocinante, donkey, tree, mountains..); Cardenio'sscorzois crude.
1 - Copy after Savery's original composition (Dordrecht: Savery, 1657; also copied for Brussels: Mommarte, 1662; Amberes: Verdussen, 1672 - 1673).
Don Quixote does Pennance upon the Mountain

Copy from Bouttats' composition (Amberes: Verdussen, 1672 - 1673). Sancho, with a broom bunch, says goodbye to don Quixote, while the knight remains doing penance (doing a somersault). In this illustration, the engraving is better than in the previous one, and has more details (Rocinante, armour, clothes, tree, mountains...).
The Strange Adventures in the Inn
36.2 Resolution of love affairs of Cardenio and Luscinda, Dorotea and Don Fernando

Copy from Savery's composition (Drodrecht: Savery, 1657; Brussels: Mommarte, 1662; Amberes: Verdussen, 1672 - 1673); now, the engraver is more simple (details in clothes and faces have been simplified). In the foreground, from right to left: Luscinda and don Fernando, just arrived at the inn, Dorotea, Sancho and Cardenio.
Previous to this illustration, there should be another one: "Sancho corrected for Blafpheming against Dilcinea" (f.p. 236).
Don Quixote Enchanted by the Inn Keeper's Daughter
43.2 Maritornes and innkeeper’s daughter hang DQ from window by a hand43.3 Four travelers arrive at inn

Copy from Bouttats' composition (Amberes: Verdussen, 1672 - 1673). Don Quixote remains hung by his hand when four travelers (servants of don Luis's father)arrive to the inn. The innkeeper appears to discover who is crying. Maritornes and the inkeeper's daughter should not still appear in the window.This is one of the best plates of the set. The engraving is well detailed (Rocinante, don Quixote's armour, horses, clothes, faces...).
45.1 Dispute at inn about the Mambrino’s helmet and packsaddle (albarda)

Copy from Savery's composition (Dordrecht: Savery, 1657; Brussels: Mommarte, 1662; Amberes: Verdussen, 1672 - 1673). In the center of the composition, don Quixote, who shouts to calm down the fighting around him. In the left, Sancho and a barber fight for the packsaddle.The engraving is bad. Figures and gestures have been much simplified.
Next to this illustration, there should be another one, the last in Part I: "The Adventures of the Goatherd and the Procefsion" (f.p. 407).
Don Quixote meets the Lady Dulcinea Enchanted by sancho
10.2 The three labradoras10.3 SP presents to DQ the enchanted Dulcinea

Copy from Bouttats' plate (Amberes: Verdussen, 1672 - 1673). Well balanced composition with two different scenes. The first one in the foreground: left, don Quixote knelt down and one peasant girl with her donkey; center, "Dulcinea" and her donkey; right, Sancho Panza knelt down and another peasant girl with her donkey. The second scene in the background: the three peasant girls flee from don Quixote and one of them falls from her donkey, showing her ass (humorous).

In Cushing's copy, the Part II frontispiece is missing. It was the same one done for Part I and was signed by M. van der Gucht. It contained the figures of don Quixote and Rocinante, Sancho and his donkey, two statues (Amadis and Orlando) and two medallions (Dulcinea and Merlin). M. van der Gucht copied Savery's Part I frontispiece (Dordrecht: Savery, 1657), including Merlin's medallion from Savery's Part II frontispiece.
Don Quixot's Encounter with the Players
11.1 Adventure of the cart of actors; “cortes de la muerte”

Copy from Savery's composition (Dordrecht: Savery, 1657; Brussels: Mommarte, 1662; Amberes: Verdussen, 1672 - 1673). In the foreground, the "bojiganga", who has stolen Sancho's donkey. Behind, the squire, who goes to don Quixote's assistance. This moment, don Quixote falling from Rocinante, is the most humorous of the episode and is situated in the background. In the cart, the players of Angulo Malo's company for the "Cortes de la Muerte" (Devil, Cupid, Death, Angel, Emperor, Queen and Soldier). There is one more player having nothing to do with Cervantes' text.
The Knight of the Looking Glafses vanquifh'd by Don Quixote
14.2 DQ defeats the knight of the Mirrors

Copy from Bouttats' composition (Amberes: Verdussen, 1672 - 1673). Two different scenes in the same plate. In the background, the first one: During the night, Sancho and the Knight of the Mirrors' squire have dinner, while their masters talk. In the foreground, the second scene: In the morning, don Quixote defeats the Knight of the Mirrors (Sansón Carrasco) and his squire (Tomé Cecial) tries to stop him. Sancho observes astonished Sansón Carrasco's face. Tomé Cecial should appear with a false big nose.
Don Quixot's Adventure with the Lyons

Copy from the basic composition for this episode created by Savery (Dordrecht: Savery, 1657; Brussels: Mommarte, 1662; Amberes: Verdussen, 1672 - 1673). In the foreground, don Quixote prepares to fight the lion while the lionkeeper opens the gate of the cage. In the background, Sancho and don Diego de Miranda keep away.
Don Quixote Descends into Montefino's cave
22.2 Adventure of the cave of Montesinos

Copy from the basic composition for this episode created by Savery (Dordrecht: Savery, 1657; Brussels: Mommarte, 1662; Amberes: Verdussen, 1672 - 1673). Don Quixote is surprised by a flock of birds when he tries to descend into Montesinos' cave. Sancho Panza and Basilio's cousin hold the rope with which don Quixote is tied. The lack of expressions make this illustration not much convincing.
Previous to this illustration, there should be another one: "Sancho flies from the Scullions who would Lather his Beard" (f.p. 102).
Don Quixote's Encounter with the puppets
26.3 DQ attacks and destroys the puppets

Copy from the basic composition for this episode created by Savery (Dordrecht: Savery, 1657; Brussels: Mommarte, 1662; Amberes: Verdussen, 1672 - 1673). Don Quixote attacks Maese Pedro's theatre while several astonished witnesses observe him. Maese Pedro appears from under the theatre. Gestures are theatrical, but without force.The engraving is acceptable.

Copy from the composition for this episode created by Bouttats (Amberes: Verdussen, 1672 - 1673).Tho different scenes in the same plate.In the foreground, don Quixote and Sancho, who falls from his donkey, are attacked by the braying mayors squadron.Lances are multiplied to suggest agitation and a more numerous group.In the background, don Quixote and Sancho keep away.Taking into consideration the number of figures, different positions and gestures, the engraving is of acceptable quality.
Don Quixote and Sancho Ride blindfold through the Air upon a Wooden Horse
41.2 DQ and SP fly on Clavileño

Copy from Savery's composition for this episode (Dordrecht: Savery, 1657; Brussels: Mommarte, 1662; Amberes: Verdussen, 1672 - 1673). In the foreground, don Quixote and Sancho ridind Clavileño; two servants simulate its flight with a bellow and fire; another servant is lighting a fuse. In the background, under a rich tent, the Duke and the Duchess observe the scene.The engraving is good. The light/shadows effects (fire and night) must be highlighted.
Previous to this illustration, another one is missing: "Merlin gives Notice how Dulcinea is to be Difenchanted" (f.p. 205).
